{
  "descriptions": [
    {
      "description": "An educational cross-section illustration of a single digital message being wrapped in successive transparent layers as it moves through a network stack. Show the innermost content as a simple data block, then two to three surrounding layers added around it, each layer visually distinct by color or thickness, to emphasize that the message is not sent naked but enclosed in extra information. Include arrows showing the wrapping direction from inner content outward.",
      "kind": "image"
    },
    {
      "description": "A layered packaging scene using a gift metaphor: a small gift box inside a larger shipping box, with a mail bag around the outside. Each layer should be shown enclosing the previous one, with the composition clearly conveying nested packaging rather than separate items. Use a clean instructional style and make the layers visually different so the nesting is obvious.",
      "kind": "image"
    },
    {
      "description": "A cutaway illustration of a parcel where the center object is the actual content and the surrounding shell represents metadata layers. The payload should remain unchanged in the middle while thin outer strips and envelopes visually surround it, showing that the original content stays inside while extra control information is added around it.",
      "kind": "image"
    },
    {
      "description": "A structured comparison table with three columns: \"Layer\", \"Adds\", \"Purpose\". Rows should be: application layer | sender and message meaning | identifies what the data represents; transport layer | error checking and ordering info | helps reliable delivery; network layer | addressing and routing info | guides movement across networks; link layer | local delivery details | moves data on the next hop. Make the rows concise and educational.",
      "kind": "table"
    },
    {
      "description": "A nested-layer diagram with four nodes: \"Original data\", \"Header 1\", \"Header 2\", \"Packet\". Show \"Original data\" flowing into \"Header 1\" to become a larger unit, then that whole unit flowing into \"Header 2\" to form the final \"Packet\". Use unique edge labels such as \"becomes payload for\", \"is wrapped by\", and \"forms\" so the structure shows how each new layer treats the previous one as its payload.",
      "kind": "diagram"
    },
    {
      "description": "A two-column table titled as a conceptual comparison of views of the same bytes. Columns: \"Layer view\" and \"What it calls the bytes\". Rows: application | message; transport | segment payload; network | packet payload; link | frame payload. Make clear that the same content is interpreted differently at each layer even though the bytes themselves do not change.",
      "kind": "table"
    },
    {
      "description": "A network forwarding diagram with four nodes: \"Application data\", \"Packet\", \"Router\", \"Next hop\". Show the message being wrapped into a packet before reaching the router; then the router reading only the outer packet information and forwarding it onward to the next hop while the inner message remains hidden. Use distinct edge labels like \"encapsulates into\", \"inspects outer header\", and \"forwards to\".",
      "kind": "diagram"
    },
    {
      "description": "A step-by-step unwrapping diagram with four nodes: \"Received packet\", \"Remove outer header\", \"Inner packet\", \"Delivered data\". Show the packet entering from the network side, then each layer stripping off its own wrapper, passing the remaining inner contents upward until the original data is delivered. Use unique labels such as \"decapsulates\", \"passes upward\", and \"reveals\".",
      "kind": "diagram"
    },
    {
      "description": "A simple before-and-after comparison table with columns \"With encapsulation\" and \"Without encapsulation\". Rows: \"Layer independence\" | \"Each layer can change within its contract\" | \"Changes ripple everywhere\"; \"Interoperability\" | \"Devices agree on shared interfaces\" | \"No clear delivery rules\"; \"Maintenance\" | \"Easier to update one part\" | \"Harder to redesign the whole stack\". Keep the tone instructional and focused on modularity.",
      "kind": "table"
    },
    {
      "description": "A side-by-side comparison table with columns \"Concept\", \"What it does\", \"Does it hide content?\", \"Does it shrink content?\". Rows: encapsulation | wraps data with headers and trailers | no | no; encryption | converts content so it cannot be read without a key | yes | no; compression | reduces size by encoding content more efficiently | no | yes. The table should clearly separate packaging from secrecy and size reduction.",
      "kind": "table"
    },
    {
      "description": "A table titled \"Header job examples\" with columns \"Header information\", \"Used for\", \"Why it matters\". Rows: destination address | routing and delivery | tells devices where the packet should go; error check | detecting corruption | helps catch damaged data; sequence info | ordering pieces correctly | keeps fragments in the right order; protocol type | choosing how to interpret contents | tells the next layer what to expect. Make the headers look like purposeful control data, not random overhead.",
      "kind": "table"
    },
    {
      "description": "A final summary image showing a message traveling through several network devices as a protected bundle. Use a layered package moving along a path from sender to receiver, with each intermediate device touching only the outer shell. The scene should communicate the big idea of one message being carried safely through many systems that each understand only their own layer, without any visible text.",
      "kind": "image"
    },
    {
      "description": "A final conceptual diagram with three nodes: \"Wrapped data\", \"Many network systems\", \"Received message\". Show the data moving through multiple systems while staying layered until the final node receives the unwrapped content. Use distinct edges such as \"travels through\", \"is interpreted by\", and \"emerges as\" to emphasize that one message can pass through many partial viewpoints.",
      "kind": "diagram"
    }
  ]
}

