{
  "descriptions": [
    {
      "description": "Create a clean educational infographic in English showing who is included in the unemployment rate. Use two side-by-side groups: one labeled \"In the labor force\" with small icons for employed people and actively searching people, and another labeled \"Outside the labor force\" with icons for people not working and not looking. Add a simple inclusion boundary around the labor force group to make clear that the unemployment rate counts only those inside it. No extra statistics, just clear visual separation and labels.",
      "kind": "diagram"
    },
    {
      "description": "Create a two-part comparison table in English with columns \"Condition\", \"Counted as unemployed?\", and \"Why\". Rows: \"Has no job, available, actively looking\" → \"Yes\" → \"Meets all three criteria\"; \"Has no job, but not searching\" → \"No\" → \"Not actively looking\"; \"Has a job\" → \"No\" → \"Employed, not unemployed\". The table should make the rule for unemployment explicit and easy to scan.",
      "kind": "table"
    },
    {
      "description": "Create a formula-centered educational graphic in English showing the unemployment rate definition as a displayed equation: \"u = U / LF\", with a second line expanding \"LF = E + U\". Include brief annotations that U means unemployed people, E means employed people, and LF means labor force. Make the denominator distinction visually prominent.",
      "kind": "formula"
    },
    {
      "description": "Create a simple worked-example table in English with columns \"Group\", \"Number of people\", and \"Role in the rate\". Rows: \"Employed\" → 60 → \"Included in labor force\"; \"Unemployed and searching\" → 5 → \"Numerator and labor force\"; \"Not working and not searching\" → 35 → \"Outside labor force\"; \"Labor force total\" → 65 → \"60 + 5\"; \"Unemployment rate\" → 7.7% → \"5 ÷ 65\". Highlight the contrast between the labor-force denominator and the full population of 100 adults.",
      "kind": "table"
    },
    {
      "description": "Create an image of a small crowd at a job fair with a spotlight focused on a few active job seekers and employed workers, while a separate group stands outside the spotlight calmly going about daily life. The composition should suggest that the statistic measures participation in the job market rather than overall well-being. No visible text in the image.",
      "kind": "image"
    },
    {
      "description": "Create a two-path conceptual table in English with columns \"Labor market change\", \"What happens to search\", \"Effect on unemployment rate\". Rows: \"Workers give up searching\" → \"Search falls\" → \"Rate may stay flat or fall\"; \"Workers keep searching unsuccessfully\" → \"Search continues\" → \"Rate rises\". The table should show how discouragement can hide weakness in the labor market.",
      "kind": "table"
    },
    {
      "description": "Create a cycle diagram in English with five nodes: \"Job loss\", \"Unemployment\", \"Job finding\", \"Employment\", and \"Rate changes\". Show directed flow from Job loss to Unemployment, Unemployment to Job finding, Job finding to Employment, Employment back to Job loss, and a feedback arrow from changes in these flows to Rate changes. Use unique edge labels such as \"enters\", \"searches\", \"exits to\", \"cycles back to\", and \"shifts with\". The diagram should emphasize that the unemployment rate is a stock shaped by inflow and outflow.",
      "kind": "diagram"
    },
    {
      "description": "Create a comparison table in English with columns \"Situation\", \"Main reason for unemployment\", and \"Same unemployment rate, different meaning\". Rows: \"Many layoffs\" → \"More people recently lost jobs\" → \"High rate due to inflow\"; \"Long unemployment spells\" → \"People stay unemployed longer\" → \"High rate due to slow exit\". Make clear that the same rate can reflect different underlying labor market realities.",
      "kind": "table"
    },
    {
      "description": "Create a timeline in English with four milestones: \"Normal job changing\" — \"Even in good times, people move between jobs, graduate, or reenter work\"; \"Matching takes time\" — \"Some unemployment exists because workers and vacancies do not match instantly\"; \"Low but nonzero unemployment\" — \"Healthy economies still have some jobless search\"; \"Zero is rare\" — \"The rate almost never reaches zero because turnover never fully stops\". Use a clean horizontal layout.",
      "kind": "timeline"
    },
    {
      "description": "Create a comparison table in English with columns \"Type of unemployment\", \"Typical economy\", and \"What it signals\". Rows: \"Normal turnover\" → \"Expanding or stable\" → \"Routine job transitions\"; \"Recession-related unemployment\" → \"Weak economy\" → \"Fewer openings, slower hiring, longer jobless spells\". The table should contrast ordinary friction with broad downturn weakness.",
      "kind": "table"
    },
    {
      "description": "Create an educational diagram in English centered on the unemployment rate as a focused measure. Show three surrounding nodes connected to a central node: \"Who is counted\", \"Who is searching\", and \"How people flow in and out\". Use unique edge labels like \"defines the boundary of\", \"determines the numerator of\", and \"changes through\". Keep the design restrained and analytical, emphasizing that the measure is useful but incomplete.",
      "kind": "diagram"
    },
